I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation to establish relationships with artists without being expected to view them critically.
We grew up in an age of media glory, with a collective awareness of popular culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, as it was not that easy to determine that back then.
We did not need to question the podium on which we placed them. These parasocial relationships were so important and have influenced our lives.
Therefore, we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the show together.
This was very different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once, and everyone watches whenever they feel like it and posts on social media with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we yearn for this universal community that once dominated everything.
That's why so many of us still watch shows like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman" with such gusto, where so many one-liners were uttered that would be memes today.
We have brought all these sayings and assumed that most of them are already understood.
Today, one can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it is massively shared virally.
There is far too much, and there is no way to systematize it. Can we possibly get out of this overabundance at all?
We are trapped in a vicious cycle, constantly discovering new content, only to then realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
Therefore, we must hold on to our nostalgia and simultaneously accept that the people who created the works we like can also have made great mistakes.
We approach parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We realize that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes along the way.
As our collective awareness regarding media has diminished, we have developed a class consciousness that fosters our critical thinking.
There are still those among us who elevate someone to a pedestal only to be shocked when they fall.
We are in a phase of transition, and I am curious to see where it will ultimately lead.
